******
[3]
Date: Wed 9 Oct 2013
Source: The New Indian Express [summ., edited]
http://newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/High-alert-against-foot-and-mouth-disease/2013/10/09/article1826670.ece


All check posts along the borders with Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu and Kerala have been alerted not to let any cattle in from those states. All Deputy Commissioners across the State [Karnataka] have banned cattle or sheep fairs. And government officials are watching the skies, hoping the rain will stop.

The dreaded foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) has spread to 17 482 cows and buffaloes and killed 2182 in 1368 villages of 7 South Karnataka districts. It does not affect humans or the milk produced by the cattle.

Animal husbandry officials admitted that there is cause for panic among the farmers. "For the last 5 years, we did not have very heavy rains, so the average temperature remained normal. We have not seen any major outbreak of the FMD at all. Now, because of the very heavy rainfall over the last few months, the temperature has been low, leading to a large scale breeding of the FMD virus," Co-Director (Livestock Health) Dr Nagaraj Shetty told Express.

Farmers, however, maintained that an ego clash between the Animal Husbandry Department and Karnataka Milk Federation (KMF) had led to the situation.

The department figures show that 1.04 crore [10 400 000] of the 1.25 crore [12 500 000] cattle in the state have completed the August-September round of vaccinations under the Central scheme. "We will cover the rest within the next 2 weeks. We are confident we will control this outbreak," Commissioner Mohammed Salahuddin said.

Officials contended that farmers have not taken sufficient care to get all their cattle vaccinated, as there is fear that the cows will stop giving milk and the pregnant cows will abort, if vaccinated. "The cows may not give milk for one week, after which they will be fine. The FMD can be fatal, the farmers should realise this. And if the cow is pregnant, they should get it vaccinated after the calf is born, they don't do that," Salahuddin rued.

Siddaramaiah has set up a 7-member committee under former vice-chancellor of the Karnataka Veterinary, Animal and Fisheries Sciences University, Dr Aryan Srinivas Gowda, to further investigate causes for the outbreak. There is a fear that the virus might have mutated and overpowered the vaccine.

[Byline: Sowmya Aji]

